{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504571"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2342"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2342"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.04,0.36,0.21,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83246"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68266"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4137"},{"type":"tags","id":"4548"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83246"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of increasing urinary leakage. The leakage occurs with coughing and straining. She denies dysuria or urinary frequency. She has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Her regular medications include salbutamol and inhaled corticosteroids. She maintains a well-balanced, high-fibre diet with regular bowel movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender with no masses palpable. Vaginal examination with a chaperone reveals no visible pelvic organ prolapse. Urinalysis is negative for leukocytes and nitrites. She has previously tried pelvic floor exercises with a physiotherapist for six months without improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxybutynin","Solifenacin","Colposuspension","Duloxetine","Botulinum injections"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with stress urinary incontinence (SUI), characterised by urinary leakage with increased intra-abdominal pressure such as coughing or straining. Her chronic cough likely exacerbates the condition. Having failed conservative management with pelvic floor exercises, surgical intervention may now be considered. Patients may also consider topical oestrogen if vaginal atrophy is a contributing factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColposuspension\u003C/strong\u003E (burch colposuspension) is an appropriate surgical option for SUI that has failed conservative management. The procedure supports the bladder neck and proximal urethra, with good long-term success rates. It is particularly suitable for women with significant symptoms impacting quality of life who have failed conservative measures.  Urethral bulking and mid-urethral slings are other surgical considerations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxybutynin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticholinergic medication used for overactive bladder syndrome, characterised by urgency, frequency, and urge incontinence. It would not address the underlying anatomical defect causing stress incontinence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolifenacin\u003C/strong\u003E, like oxybutynin, is another anticholinergic medication for overactive bladder. It is not appropriate for pure stress incontinence as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuloxetine\u003C/strong\u003E can be used off-label for SUI by increasing neurotransmitter activity affecting urinary muscle tone. However, its effects are modest and it is generally considered when surgery is contraindicated and as a second-line option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulinum injections\u003C/strong\u003E are for treatment of overactive bladder symptoms after lifestyle interventions, bladder training exercises and medications. This would not be appropriate treatment for stress incontinence and may worsen her symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colposuspension is indicated for stress urinary incontinence that has failed conservative management and significantly impacts quality of life","Stress urinary incontinence presents with urinary leakage on increased intra-abdominal pressure (coughing, sneezing, exercise)","Pelvic floor exercises are the first treatment option for stress incontinence."],"references":["Treatment Options for Stress Urinary Incontinence (SUI). In: Australian commission on safety and quality in healthcare. 2019. Available at: https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/sites/default/files/migrated/Treatment-Options-SUI-Consumer-Info.pdf.","Fitz FF, Gimenez MM, de Azevedo Ferreira L, et al. Pelvic floor muscle training for female stress urinary incontinence: a randomised control trial comparing home and outpatient training. Int Urogynecol J 2020; 31:989. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31444535/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68266"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68266"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-02T19:27:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-02T19:28:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83246"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt"